\begin_layout Section*
Parametrization using Transcendental Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Points 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 lie on unit circles centred at 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{U}=(0,-\frac{1}{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{V}=(0,\frac{1}{2})$
\end_inset

 respectively as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 correspond to points 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U\left(t\right)=\left[\sin\left(t\right),-\frac{1}{2}-\cos\left(t\right),0\right]\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $T'UV$
\end_inset

 is formed by the joining line 
\begin_inset Formula $UV$
\end_inset

 and the intersection point 
\begin_inset Formula $T'$
\end_inset

 of the tangent lines through 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Point 
\begin_inset Formula $T'$
\end_inset

 is also the inverse of point 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{U}=(0,-\frac{1}{2}-\cos\left(t\right))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By inversion with respect to the circle, the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{U}T'$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|C_{U}T'|=\frac{1}{\cos\left(t\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

