\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, the circle centred at 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{V}$
\end_inset

 is rotated from yz into the xy plane.
 Since the circle centres are unit distance apart, the length 
\begin_inset Formula $T'C_{V}$
\end_inset

 is therefore
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|T'C_{V}|=1+\frac{1}{\cos\left(t\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T_{V}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $T'$
\end_inset

 with respect to the upper circle, making the displacement along the y axis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|C_{V}T_{V}|=\frac{1}{1+\frac{1}{\cos\left(t\right)}}=\frac{\cos\left(t\right)}{1+\cos\left(t\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
By Pythagoras, the squared distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to the y axis is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|VT_{V}|^{2}=1-\frac{\cos^{2}\left(t\right)}{\left(1+\cos\left(t\right)\right)^{2}}=\frac{1+2\cos\left(t\right)}{\left(1+\cos\left(t\right)\right)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Rotating back into the yz plane it follows that V has the parametrization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(t\right)=\left[0,\frac{1}{2}-\frac{\cos\left(t\right)}{1+\cos\left(t\right)},\pm\frac{\sqrt{1+2\cos\left(t\right)}}{1+\cos\left(t\right)}\right]\label{eq:2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Alternative Quasi-Rational Parametrization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
